{
  "doc_id": "48717",
  "text": "Elevated expression of EGFR is associated with highly aggressive and metastatic cancers, including cancer of the breast [CITATION_1] . As a member of the ErbB family of receptor tyrosine kinases, EGFR has been characterized as a proto-oncogene. EGFR and other ErB receptors may be upregulated or mutated in cancer and this results in changes in downstream signaling partners which can contribute to resistance mechanisms employed by cancer cells. This ability of EGFR, to function despite treatment with tyrosine kinase inhibitors and targeting antibodies, poses a major problem for cancer therapy [CITATION_2] . Thus, an understanding of EGFR signaling cascades is vital in the production of specific therapies targeting metastasis.",
  "correct_citation": {
